          <!-- ============================ (6) FAQ ============================ -->
          <section id="faq" class="bg-slate-50 border-y border-slate-200">
            <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-14">
              <h2 class="text-3xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-slate-900 text-center">Frequently asked questions</h2>
              <p class="mt-3 text-center text-slate-600">Common questions about furnace sizing, BTUs, and AFUE.</p>
      
              <div class="mt-8 space-y-3">
                <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
                  <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                    How many BTUs of heat do I need per square foot?
                    <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-orange-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"/></svg>
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Heating needs run from about <strong>30 to 60 BTU per square foot</strong> depending on climate. Hot southern climates need roughly 30–35, moderate climates 40–45, and very cold northern climates 50–60. Insulation quality moves the number up or down about 10%.</p>
                </details>
      
                <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
                  <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                    What size furnace do I need for a 2,000 square foot house?
                    <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-orange-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"/></svg>
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">In a moderate climate at 45 BTU/sq ft, a 2,000 sq ft home needs about <strong>90,000 BTU of heat output</strong>. With a 95% AFUE furnace that means roughly 95,000 BTU of input — so a <strong>100,000 BTU furnace</strong>. In warm climates an 80,000 BTU unit often suffices.</p>
                </details>
      
                <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
                  <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                    What's the difference between furnace input and output BTU?
                    <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-orange-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"/></svg>
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed"><strong>Input</strong> is the fuel energy a furnace burns; <strong>output</strong> is the heat it actually delivers. Output = input × AFUE. An 80,000 BTU input furnace at 95% AFUE delivers 76,000 BTU of heat. Furnaces are sold by input rating, which is why this calculator converts for you.</p>
                </details>
      
                <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
                  <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                    What does AFUE mean on a furnace?
                    <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-orange-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"/></svg>
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">AFUE stands for <strong>Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency</strong> — the percentage of fuel converted into usable heat over a season. A standard furnace is about 80% AFUE; high-efficiency condensing furnaces reach 95–97%. Higher AFUE means you can buy a smaller input rating for the same delivered heat.</p>
                </details>
      
                <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
                  <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                    Is a bigger furnace always better?
                    <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-orange-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"/></svg>
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">No. An oversized furnace heats the air fast and shuts off — a pattern called <strong>short-cycling</strong> that causes uneven temperatures, wasted fuel, and extra wear on the heat exchanger and blower. A right-sized furnace runs longer, steadier, more comfortable cycles.</p>
                </details>
      
                <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
                  <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                    What furnace sizes are available?
                    <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-orange-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"/></svg>
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Residential gas furnaces are typically sold in input ratings of <strong>40,000, 60,000, 80,000, 100,000, and 120,000 BTU</strong>, with some brands offering 45,000, 70,000, or 140,000 BTU models. Calculate your required input, then round up to the nearest size your brand offers.</p>
                </details>
      
                <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
                  <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                    How accurate is this vs. a Manual J load calculation?
                    <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-orange-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"/></svg>
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">This tool gives a fast planning estimate from the factors that matter most: area, climate, insulation, and efficiency. A full <strong>ACCA Manual J</strong> calculation also accounts for windows, orientation, air infiltration, and duct losses — and is required for permits and equipment warranties. Use this to plan and a Manual J to install.</p>
                </details>
              </div>
            </div>
          </section>
      
